definition.value: A biological macromolecule minimally consisting of one polypeptide chain synthesized at the ribosome.
A hydroxybenzoate that is the  conjugate base of dihydroxybenzoic acid.
A coumaric acid in which the hydroxy substituent is located at C-4 of the phenyl ring.
A class of esterified prostanoids obtained from marine corals.
A monocarboxylic acid that consists of cyclohexane substituted by a carboxy group.
The simplest member of the class of neoflavans, that is 3,4-dihydro-2H-1-benzopyran substituted by a phenyl group at position 4.
The (S)-enantiomer of isoflavan.
The (R)-enantiomer of isoflavan.
The (R)-enantiomer of flavan.
The (S)-enantiomer of flavan.
The (R)-enantiomer of flavanone.
A naphthoic acid that is naphthalene carrying a carboxy group at position 2.
A naphthoate that is the conjugate base of 2-naphthoic acid.

A naphthoic acid with the carboxy group at position 2 and carrying a hydroxy substituent at the 1-position. It is a  xenobiotic metabolite produced by the biodegradation of phenanthrene by microorganisms.
A benzodiazepine that is 3H-1,4-benzodiazepine 4-oxide substituted by a chloro group at position 7, a phenyl group at position 5 and a methylamino group at position 2.
A piperidinecarboxylate that is the  conjugate base of pipecolic acid.
Any member of the class of  pyridines carrying two carboxy groups.
An anthocyanidin cation that is flavylium substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3.
A member of the class of chromenyliums that is chromene with a protonated oxygen.
An organic cation that is isochromene with a protonated oxygen.
The simplest member of the class of pyryliums that is pyran with a protonated oxygen.
A member of the class of chromenyliums that is chromenylium with a phenyl substituent at position 2.
A member of the class of anthocyanin chlorides that has pelargonidin 3-O-beta-D-glucoside as the cationic counterpart.
The (+)-enantiomer of quinic acid.
A  dihydroxyflavone that is flavone substituted by a chloro group at position 3', hydroxy groups at positions 5 and 2' and methoxy groups at positions 3, 7 band 8 respectively.
An alicyclic ketone in which the carbocyclic ring structure forms part of a terpene skeleton.
A cyclic ketone in which the carbocyclic ring structure which may be saturated or unsaturated, but may not be a benzenoid or other aromatic system.
A pentenedioate that is the dianion obtained by the deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of glutaconic acid.
A bisbiguanide compound with a structure consisting of two (p-chlorophenyl)guanide units linked by a hexamethylene bridge.
Any alicyclic ketone that consists of a cyclopentane skeleton substituted by at least one oxo group.
